instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The DT framework follows a modular architecture pattern with standardized extension points, enabling custom service integration and analytics. A central hub facilitates bidirectional data exchange between the physical building and the digital twin and provides a holistic approach to building lifecycle management. Runtime configuration management allows adaptability without full redeployment, supporting coordination among roles such as Building Control Engineers, Facility Managers, and DT Engineers."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "Initiation – Building control engineers enrich BIM models with sensor, actuator and controller elements, addressing BIM’s static limitations; Transformation – Using model‑driven engineering (MDE) the framework extracts structured representations from the enriched BIM and automatically generates deployable Digital‑Twin artifacts (model‑based digital assets); Deployment – Devices are provisioned, real‑time data‑exchange links are established to keep the digital twin synchronized with the physical building; Operation – Facility managers monitor the twin through immersive visualization dashboards, control physical infrastructure via the twin, and provide feedback for tuning; Evolution – DT engineers extend functionality by publishing custom services or analytics through standardized extension points; the modular architecture supports versioning and rollback. Governance is enforced through actor roles (Building Control Engineer, Facility Manager, DT Engineer) and lifecycle checkpoints defined in the deployment framework."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is maintained by validating enriched BIM models against defined schemas before conversion. Eclipse Ditto’s policy‑based validation enforces value ranges, units, and consistency for incoming sensor measurements, thereby preventing out‑of‑range data from corrupting the twin. Fault tolerance is achieved through Eclipse Hono’s at‑least‑once delivery semantics and Ditto’s persistent event storage, which safeguard against transient network failures. Pre‑execution checks for actuator commands ensure that potentially unsafe or conflicting actuations are rejected before reaching the physical device. The framework’s modular architecture allows for the integration of additional verification layers (e.g., simulation‑based validation) at defined extension points, thus supporting continuous quality assurance throughout the DT lifecycle."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "The DT framework emphasizes interoperability across heterogeneous systems, supporting integration of external systems via standardized extension points and real‑time data exchange mechanisms. Specific data exchange protocols or interoperability standards are not detailed in the provided documents."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The framework aims for interoperability via bidirectional real‑time communication but does not specify compliance with particular industry standards; it acknowledges the absence of standardized data schemas and robust integration frameworks in many AECO deployments. Existing open‑source platforms such as Eclipse Ditto and BaSyx provide standard compliance for connectivity but require manual configuration, highlighting the need for automated, standard‑aligned solutions in AECO contexts."
]
